---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
---
<Base title="The Dashboard as CYA" section={1}>
  <SectionHeader n={1} title="The Dashboard as CYA" meta="~500w" />

  <div class="prose">

    <p>
      Every organisation has dashboards nobody reads. You know the ones — sixteen panels,
      four different date filters, a donut chart in the corner that has been wrong for
      three months and nobody has noticed. They refresh every five minutes. They live on
      a screen in a corridor, watched only by people waiting for the lift.
    </p>

    <p>
      These dashboards exist. They are actively maintained. Someone built them, someone
      approved the budget, someone sends a screenshot in the all-hands every quarter.
      And yet they do not help anyone decide anything. If they disappeared overnight,
      the business would continue operating exactly as before.
    </p>

    <p>
      So why do they exist?
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      <p>Dashboards get built for the presenter, not the reader. They exist to demonstrate
      that someone is on top of things — not to help anyone decide anything.</p>
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      The honest answer is that dashboards are cover. They are a form of organisational
      CYA — Cover Your Analysis. Nobody gets fired for building a dashboard. Building one
      signals effort, diligence, investment in data. When something goes wrong, a dashboard
      is evidence that you were watching. It doesn't matter that you weren't watching the
      right thing, or that the thing you were watching didn't have an obvious threshold,
      or that the threshold wouldn't have triggered in time anyway. The dashboard was there.
      You were on it.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the original sin of dashboard culture: the dashboard was designed for the
      person being held accountable, not the person trying to make a decision. These are
      rarely the same person. The analyst builds for the VP who commissioned it. The VP
      shares it with the board. The board nods. Nothing changes. The dashboard gets
      a second tab.
    </p>

    <p>
      There is a related pathology, which is the dashboard as political object. When teams
      fight over which metrics belong on the shared screen, what they are really fighting
      over is visibility — whose work shows up, whose numbers are foregrounded, whose
      domain looks important. Data governance meetings that run three hours and accomplish
      nothing are often really budget conversations wearing data clothing. The dashboard
      becomes a proxy for org chart disputes that nobody wants to have directly.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="Pattern">
      If you cannot name the last decision your dashboard enabled — a real decision,
      made by a specific person, that changed an action — your dashboard is probably
      performing oversight rather than enabling it.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      None of this is dishonest in a cynical sense. Most dashboard builders genuinely
      believe they are providing value. They have learned to equate visibility with
      understanding, and understanding with control. The dashboard proves something is
      being watched. Surely that is better than nothing.
    </p>

    <p>
      It is not better than nothing. It is often worse. A watched metric that nobody acts
      on creates the illusion of oversight while providing none of its substance. It uses
      up attention that could be spent on the actual question. Worse, it establishes
      a social norm — this is how we do data here — that makes the actual question
      harder to ask.
    </p>

    <p>
      The fix is not a better dashboard. The fix is to ask, before building anything:
      who makes a decision with this, and what decision do they make? If you cannot answer
      that question in one sentence, you do not yet have a brief. You have a request for
      a political object dressed up in metric clothing.
    </p>

    <p>
      Stop building those.
    </p>

  </div>
</Base>
